That's expected. ODF/NooBaa protects against accidental deletion.

The webhook is blocking deletion because:

Noobaa cleanup policy is not set, blocking Noobaa deletion

Before deleting anything

Let's first try a non-destructive recovery because the problem is an authentication mismatch between the NooBaa DB and the noobaa-admin secret.

Run these commands:

oc delete pod noobaa-core-0 -n openshift-storage
oc delete pod noobaa-db-pg-0 -n openshift-storage
oc delete pod -l app=noobaa-operator -n openshift-storage

Wait until all NooBaa pods are Running again:

oc get pods -n openshift-storage | grep noobaa

Then check:

oc get noobaa -n openshift-storage


---

If still Configuring

Let's inspect the admin secret values being used:

oc get secret noobaa-admin -n openshift-storage \
-o jsonpath='{.data.email}' | base64 -d; echo

oc get secret noobaa-admin -n openshift-storage \
-o jsonpath='{.data.system}' | base64 -d; echo

Also check:

oc get secret noobaa-operator -n openshift-storage -o yaml

Sometimes after DB recreation the operator secret and admin secret are out of sync.


---

If deletion becomes necessary

You'll need to set a cleanup policy first.

Check current NooBaa spec:

oc get noobaa noobaa -n openshift-storage -o yaml | grep -A5 cleanupPolicy

Then patch it, for example:

oc patch noobaa noobaa -n openshift-storage \
--type=merge \
-p '{"spec":{"cleanupPolicy":{"confirm":"yes-really-delete-noobaa"}}}'

The exact cleanup policy format can vary by NooBaa/ODF version, so verify the current CR structure before patching.


